label: Cumulative sum Rotavirus-pos stools
definition: Cumulative sum of stool samples positive for Rotavirus by ELISA to date per participant. Any positive Rotavirus test result within 28 days of Rotavirus vaccination was changed to be a negative result. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Cumulative sum Rotavirus-pos 1st diarrheal stools
definition: Cumulative sum of first diarrheal stool samples positive for Rotavirus by ELISA to date per participant. Any positive Rotavirus test result within 28 days of Rotavirus vaccination was changed to be a negative result. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age).

label: Cumulative sum Rotavirus-pos 1st monthly stools
definition: Cumulative sum of first monthly asymptomatic stool samples positive for Rotavirus by ELISA to date per participant. Any positive Rotavirus test result within 28 days of Rotavirus vaccination was changed to be a negative result. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Virus in stool
definition: Detection of the following viruses in stool samples. Any positive Rotavirus test result within 28 days of Rotavirus vaccination was changed to be a negative result. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on diarrheal stool samples collected until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Rotavirus (post-vax corrected), by ELISA
definition: Whether Rotavirus was detected by ELISA for this stool sample. Any positive Rotavirus test result within 28 days of Rotavirus vaccination was changed to be a negative result. Whenever a participant produced at least 3 loose stools in a single day, diarrheal stool samples were collected before the end of the episode. Work up for detection of enteric pathogens was performed on the first stool sample collected during each diarrheal episode until 24 months of age (with a possible extension to 36 months of age) and on first monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected at 1-12, 15, 18, 21, and 24 months of age (with the option to test additional monthly stool samples to 36 months of age).

label: Rotavirus Ct value, by TAC result
definition: Cycle threshold for this stool sample to become positive for Rotavirus by TaqMan Array Card (TAC). This variable does not correct for positive results (Ct <35) due to Rotavirus vaccination. Ct values of 35 were negative. Quantitative PCR for detection of enteric pathogens via TAC was performed on all available diarrheal and monthly asymptomatic stool samples collected from 0-24 months and at 60 months of age.
